/jat/ Jicarilla Apache Texts]\n* [https://www.academia.edu/3552083/Midwest-Amazonian_Folklore-Mythological_Parallels \"Midwest-Amazonian\" Folklore-Mythological Parallels]\n{{Indigenous peoples of the Americas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Native American Mythology}}\n[[Category: Mythologies of the indigenous peoples of North America| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{seealso|Native American religion}}\nThe [[indigenous peoples of the Americas]] comprise numerous different cultures.  Each has its own [[mythologies]].  Some are quite distinct, but certain themes are shared across the cultural boundaries. [[Image:Coyotewithpossuminpersimmontree.png|thumb|Coyote, and Opossum appear in the stories of several tribes.]]\n\n==North America ==\n{{Refimprove section|date=August 2019}}\nThere is no single mythology of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indigenous North American]] peoples, but numerous different canons of traditional [[narrative]]s associated with [[religion]], ethics and beliefs.<ref name=\"Pearce2012\">{{cite book|author=Q. L. Pearce|title=Native American Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OVtmDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA10|date=11 May 2012|publisher=Greenhaven Publishing LLC|isbn=978-1-4205-0951-9|pages=10\u2013}}</ref> Such stories are deeply based in [[Mother Nature|Nature]] and are rich with the symbolism of seasons, weather, plants, animals, earth, water, fire, sky and the heavenly bodies. Common elements are the principle of an all-embracing, universal and omniscient [[Great Spirit]], a connection to the Earth and its landscapes, a belief in a parallel world in the sky (sometimes also underground and / or below the water), diverse creation narratives, visits to the 'land of the dead', and collective memories of ancient sacred ancestors\n\nA characteristic of many of the myths is the close relationship between human beings and animals (including birds and reptiles). They often feature shape-shifting between animal and human form. Marriage between people and different species (particularly bears) is a common theme. In some stories, animals foster human children.\n\nAlthough most Native North American myths are profound and serious, some use light-hearted humor \u2013 often in the form of tricksters \u2013 to entertain, as they subtly convey important spiritual and moral messages. The use of [[allegory]] is common, exploring issues ranging from love and friendship to domestic violence and mental illness.\n\nSome myths are connected to traditional religious rituals involving dance, music, songs, and trance (e.g. the [[sun dance]]).\n\nMost of the myths from this region were first transcribed by ethnologists during the late 19th and early 20th centuries.  These sources were collected from Native American elders who still had strong connections to the traditions of their ancestors.  They may be considered the most authentic surviving records of the ancient stories, and thus form the basis of the descriptions below. The sources quoted are available to read online through websites such as archive.org [https://archive.org]\n\n===Northeast cultures (Southeastern Canada and Northeastern US, including the Great Lakes)===\n\n[[File:FROM THE FULL MOON FELL NOKOMIS - from The Story of Hiawatha, Adapted from Longfellow by Winston Stokes and Henry Wadsworth Longfellow - Illustrator M. L. Kirk - 1910.jpg|thumb|From the full moon fell Nokomis - from The Story of Hiawatha, 1910]]\nMyths from this region feature female deities such as the creator Big Turtle <ref>{{Cite book|title=Thwaites, Reuben Gold (ed.): The Jesuit Relations and Allied Documents, Travels and Explorations of the Jesuit Missionaries in New France 1610 - 1791. Hurons, Vol. X, 1636 and Vol. XII, Quebec1637 (Cleveland: the Burrows Brothers Company, 1898)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages='What the Hurons Think of their Origin'}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barbeau|first=C M|date=1915|title=Huron and Wyandot mythology, with appendix containing earlier published records|journal=|volume=|pages='The Origin of the World'|doi=10.4095/103488|hdl=2027/uc1.32106000740347|hdl-access=free}}</ref>, and First Mother from whose body grew the first corn and tobacco.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Curtis, Natalie: The Indians' Book (New York and London: Harper and Brothers Publishers, 1907)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>, The two great divine culture heroes are Glooskap<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Leland, Charles Godfrey & Prince, John Dyneley: Kul\u00f3skap the Master, and other Algonkin Poems (New York: Funk & Wagnalls Company, 1902)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Leland, Charles G.: The Algonquin Legends of New England (Boston: Houghton, Mifflin & Co., 1884)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and Manabus.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Skinner, Alanson & Satterlee, John V.: Folklore of the Menomini Indians (New York: American Museum of Natural History, 1915)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n\nOther stories explore the complex relationships between animals and human beings. Some myths were originally recited as verse narratives.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n*[[Iroquois mythology]]\n*[[Ho-Chunk mythology]]\n*[[Wyandot religion]]\n*[[Seneca mythology]]\n\n===Great Plains cultures===\nStories unique to this region feature buffalo \u2013 the animals whose bodies provided the Plains peoples with food, clothing, housing and utensils. In some myths they are benign, in others fearsome and malevolent.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Lowie, Robert H.: Myths and Traditions of the Crow Indians (American Museum of Natural History, 1918)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> The Sun is an important deity;<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Wissler, Clark & Duvall, D.: Mythology of the Blackfoot Indians (New York: American Museum of Natural History, 1908)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Grinnell, George Bird: Blackfoot Lodge Tales \u2013 The Story of a Prairie People (New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1892)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> other supernatural characters include Morning Star<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> and the Thunderbirds.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dorsey, George A.: Wichita Tales, 1, 2 and 3 (Journal of American Folklore, 1902, 1903 and 1904)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Dorsey, James Owen: The Cehiga Language (Washington: Contributions to North American Ethnology, Government Printing Office, 1890)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nA common theme is the making of a journey, often to a supernatural place across the landscape or up to the parallel world in the sky.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Eastman, Charles A. & Eastman, Elaine Goodale: Wigwam Evenings \u2013 Sioux Folk Tales Retold (Boston: Little Brown,1909)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> One of the most dominant tricksters of the Plains is Old Man, about whom numerous humorous stories are told.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Michelson, Truman: Piegan Tales (Journal of American Folklore, 1911)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> An important supernatural hero is the Blood Clot Boy, transformed from a clot of blood.<ref>{{Cite book|title=McLaughlin, Marie L.: Myths and Legends of the Sioux (publisher unknown, 1916)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite book|title=Kroeber, A. L.: Gros Ventre Myths and Tales (New York: American Museum of Natural History, 1907)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n===Southeast US cultures===\nImportant myths of this region deal with the origin of hunting and farming,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mooney, James: Myths of the Cherokees (Journal of American Folklore, 1888)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Mooney, James: Myths of the Cherokee (Bureau of American Ethnology, 1902)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and the origin of sickness and medicine.<ref name=\":5\" />\n \nSee also:  \n*[[Cherokee mythology]]\n*[[Choctaw mythology]]\n*[[Creek mythology]]\n\n=== California and Great Basin cultures ===\nMyths of this region are dominated by the sacred creator / trickster [[Coyote (mythology)|Coyote]]. Other significant characters include the Sun People,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Barrett, S. A.: A Composite Myth of the Pomo Indians (Journal of American Folklore, 1906)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> the Star Women<ref>{{Cite book|title=Merriam, C. Hart: The Dawn of the World: Myths and Weird Tales Told by the Mewan (Miwok) Indians of California (Cleveland: Arthur H. Clarke Co., 1910)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and Darkness.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dixon, Roland B.: Achomawi and Atsugewi Tales (Journal of American Folklore, 1908 and1909)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n\nSee also:\n*[[Kuksu (religion)|Kuksu]]{{spaced ndash}}a religion in Northern California practiced by members within several [[Indigenous peoples of California]].\n*[[Miwok mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}a North American tribe in Northern [[California]].\n*[[Ohlone mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}a North American tribe in [[Northern California]].\n*[[Pomo religion]]{{spaced ndash}}a North American tribe in Northern California.\n\n=== Southwest Cultures ===\nMyths of the Navajo, Apache and Pueblo peoples tell how the first human beings emerged from an underworld to the Earth. According to the Hopi Pueblo people, the first beings were the Sun, two goddesses known as Hard Being Woman ''(Huruing Wuhti)''<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Voth, H. R.: The Traditions of the Hopi (Field Columbian Museum Publication, 190|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and Spider Woman.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=Goddard, Pliny Earle: Myths and Tales from the White Mountain Apache (New York: American Museum of Natural History, 1919|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> It was the goddesses who created living creatures and human beings. Other themes include the origin of tobacco and corn,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Lloyd, J. William: Aw-aw-tam Indian Nights, Being the Myths and Legends of the Pimas of Arizona (Westfield, N.J: The Lloyd Group, 1911)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and horses;<ref name=\":7\" /> and a battle between summer and winter. Some stories describe parallel worlds in the sky<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|title=Cushing, Frank Hamilton: Zuni Folk Tales (New York: G.P. Putman's Sons, 1901)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and underwater.<ref name=\":8\" />  \n\nSee also:\n*[[Ute mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}a North American tribe located in both the [[Northwestern United States|Northwestern]] and [[Southwestern United States]].\n*[[Din\u00e9 Bahane\u02bc]] ([[Navajo]]){{spaced ndash}}a North American nation from the Southwestern United States.\n*[[Hopi mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}a North American tribe in [[Arizona]].\n*[[Zuni mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}a North American tribe in [[New Mexico]].\n\n=== Plateau cultures ===\nMyths of the Plateau region express the people's intense spiritual feeling for their landscapes, and emphasise the importance of treating with respect the animals that they depend upon for food.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Boas, Franz (Ed): Folk-Tales of Salishan and Sahaptin Tribes (New York: American Folklore Society, 1917)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Sapir, Edward & Curtin, Jeremiah: Wishram Texts, Together with Wasco Tales and Myths (Publications of the American Ethnological Society, 1909)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Sacred tricksters here include Coyote<ref>{{Cite book|title=Teit, James: Traditions of the Thompson River Indians of British Columbia (Boston and New York: Houghton, Mifflin & Co. / London: David Nutt 1898)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and Fox.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Curtin, Jeremiah: Myths of the Modocs (Boston: Little, Brown, 1912)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nSee also:\n\n[[Salishan oral narratives|Salish mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}a North American tribe or band in Montana, [[Idaho]], Washington and [[British Columbia]], Canada\n\n===Arctic cultures (Coastal Alaska, northern Canada and Greenland)===\nThe myths of this region are strongly set in the landscape of tundra, snow, and ice. Memorable stories feature the winds, the moon, and giants. Some accounts say that Anguta is the supreme being, who created the Earth, sea and heavenly bodies. His daughter, [[Sedna (mythology)|Sedna]] created all living things \u2013 animals and plants. She is regarded also as the protecting divinity of the Inuit people.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The central Eskimo|last=author.|first=Boas, Franz, 1858-1942|oclc=11405803}}</ref>\n\n=== Subarctic cultures (Inland northern Canada and Alaska) ===\nHere some myths reflect the extreme climate<ref>{{Cite book|title=Bell, Robert: Legends of the Slavey Indians of the Mackenzie River (Journal of American Folklore, 1901)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and the people's dependence on salmon as a major food resource.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Teit, James A.: Tahltan Tales 1 and 2 (Journal of American Folklore,1921)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In imagination, the landscape is populated by both benign and malevolent giants.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Teit, James A.: Kaska Tales (Journal of American Folklore, 1917)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n=== Northwestern cultures ===\nIn this region the dominant sacred trickster is Raven, who brought daylight to the world<ref>{{Cite book|title=Swanton, John R.: Tlingit Myths and Texts (Bureau of American Ethnology, 1909)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and appears in many other stories. Myths explore the people's relationship with the coast and the rivers along which they traditionally built their towns. There are stories of visits to parallel worlds beneath the sea.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Boas, Franz: Tsimshian Mythology (Bureau of American Ethnology, 1916)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and up in the sky<ref>{{Cite book|title=Swanton, John R.: Tlingit Myths and Texts (Bureau of American Ethnology, 1909)|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> See also:\n\n*[[Kwakwaka'wakw mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}an Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast.\n*[[Lummi]]{{spaced ndash}}a North American tribe from the [[Pacific Northwest]], [[Washington (state)|Washington state]] area.\n*[[Nuu-chah-nulth mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}a a group of indigenous peoples living on [[Vancouver Island]] in British Columbia.\n*[[Haida mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}a nation living in [[Haida Gwaii]] and the [[Southeast Alaska|Alaska Panhandle]].\n*[[Tsimshian mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}an indigenous people of the Pacific Northwest Coast living on the [[British Columbia Coast]] and Alaska's [[Annette Island]]s.\n\n=== Aztec culture ===\nThe Aztecs, who predominantly inhabited modern-day central Mexico, had a complex system of beliefs based on deities who directly affected the lives of humans, including those who controlled rain, the rising Sun and fertility. Voluntary human sacrifice, was a central piece to the order of the universe and human survival. \nSee also:\n*[[Aztec mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}an ancient [[Mesoamerica|Mesoamerican]] empire centered in the valley of Mexico.\n\n==Central America ==\n* [[Maya mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}an ancient Central American people of southern Mexico and northern [[Central America]].\n* [[Olmec religion]]{{spaced ndash}}an ancient Central American people of south-central Mexico, in the present-day states of [[Veracruz]] and [[Tabasco]].\n* [[Pur\u00e9pecha religion]]{{spaced ndash}}a Central American people centered around [[Lake P\u00e1tzcuaro]].\n\n==South America ==\n* [[Chilote mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}the cultures of [[Chono]] and [[Huilliche people|Huilliche]], who live on the [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]], off the coast of southern [[Chile]].\n* [[Guarani mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}an [[Gran Chaco people|indigenous people of the Gran Chaco]], especially in [[Paraguay]] and parts of the surrounding areas of [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], and [[Bolivia]].\n* [[Inca mythology]] ([[Religion in the Inca Empire]]){{spaced ndash}}a South American empire based in the central Andes mountain range.\n* [[Mapuche religion]]{{spaced ndash}}an indigenous people of the [[Southern Cone]], especially in Chile and some regions of Argentina.\n* [[Muisca mythology]]{{spaced ndash}}the indigenous people of the [[Altiplano Cundiboyacense]] in the modern [[Cordillera Oriental (Colombia)|Eastern Ranges]] of the [[Colombia]]n Andes.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Earth-maker myth]], Native American, California.\n* [[Philippine mythology]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Rosalind Kerven (2018) ''Native American Myths collected 1636 \u2013 1919''. Talking Stone. {{ISBN|9780953745487}}\n*Erdoes, Richard and Ortiz, Alfonso: ''American Indian Myths and Legends'' (New York: Pantheon Books, 1984)\n*  Korotayev, Andrey et al. [https://www.academia.edu/37624585/Genes_and_Myths_Which_Genes_and_Myths_did_the_Different_Waves_of_the_Peopling_of_Americas_Bring_to_the_New_World Which genes and myths did the different waves of the peopling of Americas bring to the New World?. ''History and Mathematics'' 6 (2017): 9\u201377].\n*Thompson, Stith: ''Folk Tales of the North American Indians'' (Indiana University Press 1929)\n* {{cite book|author=Colin F. Taylor|title=Native American myths and legends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sxoaAQAAIAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Smithmark Publishers, Incorporated|isbn=978-0-8317-6290-2}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Sam D. Gill|author2=Irene F. Sullivan|title=Dictionary of Native American mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i7OB-BFvr9QC|year=1994|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-508602-7}}\n* {{cite book|author=Diana Ferguson|title=Native American myths|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQt1AAAAMAAJ|year=2001|publisher=Sterling Publishing Company Incorporated|isbn=978-1-85585-824-4}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Dawn Elaine Bastian|author2=Judy K. Mitchell|title=Handbook of Native American Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IsyQu1kDK-kC|year=2004|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-533-9}}\n* {{cite book|author=Fred Ramen|title=Native American Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KAjNLe2LTYAC|year=2008|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4042-0738-7}}\n* {{cite book|author1=[[Tom Lowenstein]]|author2=Piers Vitebsky|title=Native American Myths and Beliefs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fXs0ofWEIk0C|year=2011|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4488-5992-4}}\n* {{cite book|author=Hartley Burr Alexander|title=Native American Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0jG61FMpnwwC|year=2012|publisher=Dover Publications|isbn=978-0-486-12279-3}}\n* {{cite book|author=Lewis Spence|title=Native American Myths|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t5Z06Y62VY0C|year=2012|publisher=Dover Publications|isbn=978-0-486-11235-0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Q. L. Pearce|title=Native American Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7S4rYAAACAAJ|year=2012|publisher=Lucent Books|isbn=978-1-4205-0716-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130723033344/http://www.freewebs.com/apache-texts/ Apache Texts]\n* [http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/apache/ Chiricahua and Mescalero Apache Texts]\n* [http://www.sacred-texts.com/nam/pla/jat/ Jicarilla Apache Texts]\n* [https://www.academia.edu/3552083/Midwest-Amazonian_Folklore-Mythological_Parallels \"Midwest-Amazonian\" Folklore-Mythological Parallels]\n{{Indigenous peoples of the Americas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Native American Mythology}}\n[[Category: Mythologies of the indigenous peoples of North America| ]]\n", "name_user": "DinoBenn", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNortheast cultures (Southeastern Canada and Northeastern US, including the Great Lakes)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mythologies_of_the_indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas"}
{"title_page": "A Night with Janis Joplin", "text_new": "{{Infobox Musical\n| name              = A Night with Janis Joplin\n| subtitle          =\n| image             = Night with Janis Joplin playbill bway.jpg\n| image_size        = 180px\n| caption           = Original Broadway Playbill\n| music             = [[Janis Joplin]]\n| lyrics            = Janis Joplin\n| book              = Randy Johnson\n| basis             = Music of [[Janis Joplin]]\n| premiere_date     = 10 October 2013\n| premiere_location = [[Lyceum Theatre (Broadway)|Lyceum Theatre]]. [[New York City]]\n| productions       = 2013 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]\n}}\n'''''A Night with Janis Joplin''''' is a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] [[musical theatre|musical]] that includes works of singer-songwriter [[Janis Joplin]] (1943\u20131970).  After 22 previews,<ref name=gans/> it officially opened at the [[Lyceum Theatre (Broadway)|Lyceum Theatre]] on October 10, 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-verdict-critics-review-broadways-a-night-with-janis-joplin-starring-mar-210485 |title=The Verdict: Critics Review Broadway's A Night with Janis Joplin, Starring Mary Bridget Davies |date=October 11, 2013}}</ref> and closed in February, after 141 performances.<ref name=gans>{{cite news|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/a-night-with-janis-joplin-sets-closing-date-on-broadway-214290 |date=January 24, 2014 |title=A Night with Janis Joplin Sets Closing Date on Broadway |first=Andrew |last=Gans }}</ref>\n\nThe musical is presented as [[Janis Joplin]], backed by a band of hippies, performing a concert in 1970, shortly before she in fact died of drug overdose, at age 27.  Among other reviews, ''The New York Post'' characterized it as sanitizing [[Janis Joplin]] and serving as a vehicle for \"power-piped\" [[Mary Bridget Davies]] to mostly \"stick to the music\".<ref>{{cite news|title='Janis Joplin' doesn't scream Broadway |first=Elisabeth |last=Vincentelli |date=October 11, 2013 |url=https://nypost.com/2013/10/11/janis-joplin-doesnt-scream-broadway/ }}</ref>\n\nIts Broadway run was a $3.9 million production,<ref name=healy/> and $650,000 was budgeted for an Off-Broadway run that was scheduled to open at the [[Gramercy Theatre]].  The revival, however, was abruptly cancelled in April 2014, two days before it was to open.<ref name=healy>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/26/theater/how-a-night-with-janis-joplin-was-suddenly-canceled.html?_r=0 |title=It Took a Little Piece of Their Hearts: How 'A Night With Janis Joplin' Was Suddenly Canceled |last=Healy |first=Patrick |date=April 25, 2014 |work=[[The New York Times]] }}</ref>\n\nThe show performed on tour, including in [[Pasadena, California]].\n\n== Producers ==\nProducers of the original Broadway production include: Daniel Chilewich, Todd Gershwin, Michael Cohl, Jeffrey Jampol, TCG Entertainment LLC,  Red Tail Entertainment, [[Stephen Tenenbaum]], Richard Winkler, [[Michael J. Moritz Jr.]], Corey Brunish, Brisa Trinchero, Ginger Productions, Bill Ham, Claudio Loureiro, Keith Mardak, Ragovoy Entertainment LLC, Bob & Laurie Wolf, Neil Kahanovitz, Mike Stoller, Corky Hale Stroller, Darren P. Deverna, Susan DuBow, Tanya Grubich, Jeremiah J. Harris, Jerry Rosenberg, AJ Michaels, Herb Spivak, Red Awning (Executive Producer), and Nicole Kastrinos (Executive Producer).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/personlistpage/person-list|title=Person List|website=Playbill|access-date=2016-06-24}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-verdict-critics-review-broadways-a-night-with-janis-joplin-starring-mar-210485 Playbill index to reviews]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Night WIth Janis Joplin, A}}\n[[Category:Broadway musicals]]\n[[Category:2013 musicals]]\n[[Category:Jukebox musicals]]\n[[Category:Rock musicals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Musical\n| name              = A Night with Janis Joplin\n| subtitle          =\n| image             = Night with Janis Joplin playbill bway.jpg\n| image_size        = 180px\n| caption           = Original Broadway Playbill\n| music             = [[Janis Joplin]]\n| lyrics            = Janis Joplin\n| book              = Randy Johnson\n| basis             = Music of [[Janis Joplin]]\n| premiere_date     = 10 October 2013\n| premiere_location = [[Lyceum Theatre (Broadway)|Lyceum Theatre]]. [[New York City]]\n| productions       = 2013 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]\n}}\n'''''A Night with Janis Joplin''''' is a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] [[musical theatre|musical]] that includes works of singer-songwriter [[Janis Joplin]] (1943\u20131970).  After 22 previews,<ref name=gans/> it officially opened at the [[Lyceum Theatre (Broadway)|Lyceum Theatre]] on October 10, 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-verdict-critics-review-broadways-a-night-with-janis-joplin-starring-mar-210485 |title=The Verdict: Critics Review Broadway's A Night with Janis Joplin, Starring Mary Bridget Davies |date=October 11, 2013}}</ref> and closed in February, after 141 performances.<ref name=gans>{{cite news|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/a-night-with-janis-joplin-sets-closing-date-on-broadway-214290 |date=January 24, 2014 |title=A Night with Janis Joplin Sets Closing Date on Broadway |first=Andrew |last=Gans }}</ref>\n\nThe musical is presented as [[Janis Joplin]], backed by a band of hippies, performing a concert in 1970, shortly before she in fact died of drug overdose, at age 27.  Among other reviews, ''The New York Post'' characterized it as sanitizing [[Janis Joplin]] and serving as a vehicle for \"power-piped\" [[Mary Bridget Davies]] to mostly \"stick to the music\".<ref>{{cite news|title='Janis Joplin' doesn't scream Broadway |first=Elisabeth |last=Vincentelli |date=October 11, 2013 |url=https://nypost.com/2013/10/11/janis-joplin-doesnt-scream-broadway/ }}</ref>\n\nIts Broadway run was a $3.9 million production,<ref name=healy/> and $650,000 was budgeted for an Off-Broadway run that was scheduled to open at the [[Gramercy Theatre]].  The revival, however, was abruptly cancelled in April 2014, two days before it was to open.<ref name=healy>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/26/theater/how-a-night-with-janis-joplin-was-suddenly-canceled.html?_r=0 |title=It Took a Little Piece of Their Hearts: How 'A Night With Janis Joplin' Was Suddenly Canceled |last=Healy |first=Patrick |date=April 25, 2014 |work=[[New York Times]] }}</ref>\n\nThe show performed on tour, including in [[Pasadena, California]].\n\n== Producers ==\nProducers of the original Broadway production include: Daniel Chilewich, Todd Gershwin, Michael Cohl, Jeffrey Jampol, TCG Entertainment LLC,  Red Tail Entertainment, [[Stephen Tenenbaum]], Richard Winkler, [[Michael J. Moritz Jr.]], Corey Brunish, Brisa Trinchero, Ginger Productions, Bill Ham, Claudio Loureiro, Keith Mardak, Ragovoy Entertainment LLC, Bob & Laurie Wolf, Neil Kahanovitz, Mike Stoller, Corky Hale Stroller, Darren P. Deverna, Susan DuBow, Tanya Grubich, Jeremiah J. Harris, Jerry Rosenberg, AJ Michaels, Herb Spivak, Red Awning (Executive Producer), and Nicole Kastrinos (Executive Producer).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/personlistpage/person-list|title=Person List|website=Playbill|access-date=2016-06-24}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-verdict-critics-review-broadways-a-night-with-janis-joplin-starring-mar-210485 Playbill index to reviews]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Night WIth Janis Joplin, A}}\n[[Category:Broadway musicals]]\n[[Category:2013 musicals]]\n[[Category:Jukebox musicals]]\n[[Category:Rock musicals]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:the work's name is \"The New York Times\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Night_with_Janis_Joplin"}
